Sure! Here's an example of a simple Rocket WebSocket server that broadcasts one client's messages to all connected clients:

```rust
#![feature(proc_macro_hygiene, decl_macro)]

#[macro_use] extern crate rocket;
#[macro_use] extern crate rocket_contrib;
use rocket_contrib::json::Json;
use rocket::State;
use rocket::http::Status;
use rocket::serde::json::serde_json::{Value, json};
use rocket::serde::Deserialize;
use rocket::tokio::sync::broadcast;
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};

#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct Message {
    text: String,
}

#[derive(Clone)]
struct SharedData {
    sender: broadcast::Sender<Value>,
}

#[post("/message", data = "<message>")]
fn post_message(message: Json<Message>, shared_data: State<Arc<Mutex<SharedData>>>) -> Status {
    let message = message.into_inner();
    let json = json!({ "text": message.text });
    shared_data.lock().unwrap().sender.send(json).unwrap();
    Status::Accepted
}

#[get("/stream")]
async fn stream(shared_data: State<Arc<Mutex<SharedData>>>) -> broadcast::Receiver<Value> {
    shared_data.lock().unwrap().sender.subscribe()
}

#[launch]
fn rocket() -> _ {
    let (sender, _) = broadcast::channel(10);
    rocket::build()
        .manage(Arc::new(Mutex::new(SharedData { sender })))
        .mount("/", routes![post_message, stream])
}
```

In this example, we define a Rocket endpoint `/message` that accepts POST requests with JSON data representing a message. When a message is received, it is broadcast to all connected clients using the `broadcast::Sender` stored in the `SharedData` state.

We also define a `/stream` endpoint that returns a `broadcast::Receiver` to the client, allowing it to receive messages as they are broadcasted.

This example demonstrates a simple WebSocket server using Rocket that broadcasts messages from one client to all connected clients.

response_b:
Sure, here's an example of a Rocket.ws server that broadcasts one client's messages to all other clients:

1. First, you'll need to install Rocket.ws by running the following command:
```
npm install rocket-ws
```
1. Next, create a new file called `server.js` and add the following code:
```
const Rocket = require('rocket-ws');

const server = new Rocket.Server({
  // Broadcast messages to all clients
  onClientMessage: (client, message) => {
    server.broadcast(message);
  },
});

server.listen(8080, () => {
  console.log('Server listening on port 8080');
});
```
This code creates a new Rocket.ws server and sets up an event listener for when a client sends a message. When a client sends a message, the server broadcasts the message to all other clients connected to the server.

1. Now, create a new file called `client.js` and add the following code:
```
const Rocket = require('rocket-ws');

const client = new Rocket.Client('ws://localhost:8080');

client.on('open', () => {
  console.log('Client connected');

  // Send a message to the server
  client.send('Hello, server!');
});

client.on('message', (message) => {
  console.log(`Received message from server: ${message}`);
});

client.on('close', () => {
  console.log('Client disconnected');
});
```
This code creates a new Rocket.ws client and connects to the server at `ws://localhost:8080`. When the client is connected, it sends a message to the server and listens for messages from the server.

1. Finally, run the server and client scripts:
```
node server.js
node client.js
```
When you run the client script, you should see the message "Client connected" in the console, followed by the message "Received message from server: Hello, server!" When you send a message from the client to the server, the server broadcasts the message to all other clients

