Yes, you can sort a const array at compile time in C++ by using the `constexpr` keyword and taking advantage of the constexpr features. Here's an example:
```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <array>

constexpr int const_array[] = {5, 2, 9, 1, 3};

int main() {
    std::sort(std::begin(const_array), std::end(const_array));
    return 0;
}
```
In this example, the `const_array` is a constexpr array, and the `std::sort` function is used to sort the array at compile time. However, please note that this will only work if the array can be sorted at compile time. If the array contains elements that cannot be compared at compile time, you will get a compilation error.

response_b:
In C++, sorting a const array at compile time is not directly supported. However, with some template metaprogramming, it is possible to achieve this using `std::sort` in combination with `constexpr`. 

However, it's important to note that this requires a deep understanding of C++ metaprogramming and can make the code more complex and harder to read.

Here is a simple example using `std::array` and C++14's relaxed `constexpr` rules:

```cpp
#include <array>
#include <algorithm>

template <typename T, std::size_t... I>
constexpr auto sort_array(std::array<T, sizeof...(I)> arr, std::index_sequence<I...>) {
    return std::array<T, sizeof...(I)>{{(std::sort(std::begin(arr), std::end(arr)), arr[I])...}};
}

template <typename T, std::size_t N>
constexpr auto sort_array(std::array<T, N> arr) {
    return sort_array(arr, std::make_index_sequence<N>{});
}

// Usage
constexpr std::array<int, 5> arr{{5, 3, 2, 4, 1}};
constexpr auto sorted_arr = sort_array(arr);
```

Please note that C++ metaprogramming can be challenging, and the above code might be considered too complex for everyday use. It's generally simpler and more maintainable to sort arrays at runtime unless you have a good reason to do it at compile time.

