Here is some code you could use in your HTTP middleware to set the error on Datadog traces based on the Twirp error instead of a generic internal server error:

```go
import (
  "github.com/twitchtv/twirp"
  "gopkg.in/DataDog/dd-trace-go.v1/ddtrace/tracer"
)

func middleware(next http.Handler) http.Handler {
  return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    span := tracer.StartSpan("request", tracer.ResourceName("/some/endpoint"))
    defer span.Finish()

    err := next.ServeHTTP(w, r)

    // Check if error is a Twirp error
    if twerr, ok := err.(twirp.Error); ok {
      // Set error on span
      span.SetTag("error", true)
      span.SetTag("error.msg", twerr.Msg())
      span.SetTag("error.type", twerr.Error())
    } else if err != nil {
      // Handle other errors
    }
  })
}
```

The key points:

- Use `tracer.StartSpan` to start a span for the request 
- In the deferred `Finish`, check if error is a Twirp error
- If yes, set error tags on span using the Twirp error message and type 
- If no, handle other errors

This will allow Datadog to show the actual Twirp error in traces instead of a generic 500 error.

