Creating a high-quality TikZ figure to represent the recommended reading order of your PhD thesis can be done by creating a flowchart-like diagram. To highlight the important chapters, we can use different node styles. I'll provide you with a basic template, which you can then modify to fit the actual structure and content of your thesis.

First, make sure you have the `tikz` package installed. You'll also need to use the `geometry` package to set the landscape orientation for the page. Here's a simple LaTeX document with TikZ code for the diagram:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[landscape]{geometry}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric, arrows.meta, positioning}

\begin{document}
\begin{figure}[ht]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm, auto]

% Define styles for the different kinds of elements
\tikzstyle{important} = [rectangle, rounded corners, minimum width=3cm, minimum height=1cm,text centered, draw=black, fill=red!30]
\tikzstyle{normal} = [rectangle, rounded corners, minimum width=3cm, minimum height=1cm, text centered, draw=black, fill=blue!30]
\tikzstyle{arrow} = [thick,->,>=Stealth]

% Define nodes in a matrix
\matrix [column sep=5mm, row sep=5mm] {
  % row 1
  & 
ode (intro) [normal] {Introduction}; & \\
  % row 2

ode (background) [normal] {Background}; & 
ode (methodology) [important] {Methodology}; & 
ode (concepts) [normal] {Core Concepts}; \\
  % row 3
  & 
ode (contrib) [important] {Main Contributions}; & \\
  % row 4

ode (results) [important] {Results}; & 
ode (discussion) [important] {Discussion}; & 
ode (conclusion) [normal] {Conclusion}; \\
};

% Connect nodes with arrows
\draw [arrow] (intro) -- (background);
\draw [arrow] (intro) -- (methodology);
\draw [arrow] (intro) -- (concepts);
\draw [arrow] (background) -- (contrib);
\draw [arrow] (methodology) -- (contrib);
\draw [arrow] (concepts) -- (contrib);
\draw [arrow] (contrib) -- (results);
\draw [arrow] (contrib) -- (discussion);
\draw [arrow] (results) -- (conclusion);
\draw [arrow] (discussion) -- (conclusion);

\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Recommended reading order of the PhD thesis.}
\end{figure}
\end{document}
```

This code snippet provides a basic structure for your reading order flowchart:

- Introduction, Background, Core Concepts, and Conclusion are marked as "normal" chapters.
- Methodology, Main Contributions, Results, and Discussion are marked as "important" chapters and are highlighted with a different color.

You may need to adjust the matrix, node styles, and connections to accurately represent the reading order and importance of the chapters in your thesis. Simply replace the text within the nodes with the titles of your chapters, and add or remove nodes and arrows as needed.

The `\tikzstyle` command is used to define the styles for "important" and "normal" chapters, as well as the style for the arrows. The `matrix` environment is used to lay out the nodes in a grid-like fashion, and `\draw` commands are used to connect the nodes with arrows.

Remember that this is a template and you'll likely need to customize it to match the content and structure of your thesis.

