Here is an example of a React component that animates a text property as the property changes, simulating a keyboard typing effect:
```
import React, { useState } from 'react';

const TypingText = () => {
  const [text, setText] = useState('');

  const type = (char) => {
    if (text.length < 100) {
      setText(text + char);
      setTimeout(() => type(char), 100);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <p>{text}</p>
      <button onClick={() => type('a')}>Type 'a'</button>
      <button onClick={() => type('b')}>Type 'b'</button>
      <button onClick={() => type('c')}>Type 'c'</button>
    </div>
  );
};

export default TypingText;
```

This component has a `text` state variable that is used to store the current text value. The `type` function is called whenever a button is clicked, and it adds the specified character to the `text` value and schedules another call to `type` after a 100 milliseconds delay. This creates the illusion of characters being typed one at a time.
You can customize the behavior of the typing text by modifying the `type` function. For example, you could add more characters to the text as it is typed, or you could change the delay between characters. You could also use the `text` state variable to store more complex data structures and animate the display of that data in a similar way.

