When recreating the swapchain in Vulkan, you should free the command buffers that were previously allocated for the old swapchain, and then allocate new command buffers for the new swapchain.

This is because the command buffers are associated with the swapchain and are used to record commands for rendering to the swapchain images. When the swapchain is recreated, the old command buffers are no longer valid and should be freed.

To free the command buffers, you can call the `vkFreeCommandBuffers` function, passing in the old swapchain and the command buffers that were previously allocated for it. Then, you can allocate new command buffers for the new swapchain using the `vkAllocateCommandBuffers` function.

Here is an example of how you can free and reallocate command buffers when recreating the swapchain in Vulkan:
```
// Free the old command buffers
vkFreeCommandBuffers(oldSwapchain, commandBuffers);

// Allocate new command buffers for the new swapchain
VkCommandBufferAllocateInfo allocInfo = {};
allocInfo.sType = VK_STRUCTURE_TYPE_COMMAND_BUFFER_ALLOCATE_INFO;
allocInfo.commandPool = commandPool;
allocInfo.level = VK_COMMAND_BUFFER_LEVEL_PRIMARY;
allocInfo.commandBufferCount = NUM_COMMAND_BUFFERS;

VkResult result = vkAllocateCommandBuffers(newSwapchain, &allocInfo, commandBuffers);
if (result != VK_SUCCESS) {
    // Handle error
}
```
Note that you should also free any other resources that were allocated for the old swapchain, such as framebuffers and render passes, and reallocate them for the new swapchain.

