Here's a C# code that calculates all prime numbers from 1 to 100:
```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class PrimeNumbers
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        List<int> primes = GetPrimeNumbers();
        Console.WriteLine("Prime numbers from 1 to 100:");
        foreach (int prime in primes)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(prime);
        }
    }

    static List<int> GetPrimeNumbers()
    {
        List<int> primes = new List<int>();
        primes.Add(2);

        for (int i = 3; i <= 100; i += 2)
        {
            bool isPrime = true;

            for (int j = 3; j <= Math.Sqrt(i); j += 2)
            {
                if (i % j == 0)
                {
                    isPrime = false;
                    break;
                }
            }

            if (isPrime)
            {
                primes.Add(i);
            }
        }

        return primes;
    }
}
```
This code uses an iterative approach to check if a number is prime by checking if it's divisible by any number from 3 to its square root. If it's not divisible, it's added to the list of prime numbers.

