Flecs is an Entity Component System (ECS) framework for C and C++. In Flecs, an entity is a unique identifier that can be associated with a set of components. Components are data structures that hold specific attributes or variables.

To list components of a Flecs entity, you would typically iterate over the components that the entity has and print them out or process them as needed. The following example shows how you could list the components of an entity in a simple Flecs application:

```c
#include "flecs.h"

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    flecs::world ecs(argc, argv);

    // Define a component
    struct Position {
        float x, y;
    };

    ecs.component<Position>();

    // Create an entity with a Position component
    auto entity = ecs.entity()
        .set<Position>({10, 20});

    // List the components of the entity
    ecs.each([&](flecs::entity e, Position &p) {
        if (e == entity) {
            printf("Entity %llu has component Position
", static_cast<unsigned long long>(e.id()));
        }
    });

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we define a `Position` component and create an entity with this component. Then we use the `ecs.each` function to iterate over all entities that have a `Position` component. During the iteration, we check if the current entity is the one we're interested in (the one we created), and if so, we print out that it has the `Position` component.

If you want to list all components of an entity, regardless of their type, you can use the `entity.each` method which iterates over each component of a single entity:

```c
entity.each([&](flecs::id id) {
    const char *name = ecs.get_name(id);
    printf("Entity %llu has component %s
", static_cast<unsigned long long>(entity.id()), name);
});
```

In this snippet, we're using `entity.each` to iterate over each component associated with the `entity`. The `id` represents the component's identifier, and we get the component's name using `ecs.get_name(id)`.

Please note that Flecs is an actively developed framework, and the exact functions or methods may vary between versions. Always refer to the specific version of Flecs documentation or source code that you are using for the most accurate and up-to-date information.

